===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|envies}}

# [[resentful|Resentful]] desire of something possessed by another or others (but not limited to material possessions). {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
#* {{w|John Milton}} (1608-1674)
#*: No bliss enjoyed by us excites his '''envy''' more.
#* {{w|Alexander Pope}} (1688-1744)
#*: '''Envy''', to which the ignoble mind's a slave, / Is emulation in the learned or brave.
#* {{quote-book|year=1914|author={{w|Louis Joseph Vance}}
|chapter=1|title=[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/29671 Nobody]
|passage=Little disappointed, then, she turned attention to "Chat of the Social World," gossip which exercised potent fascination upon the girl's intelligence. She devoured with more avidity than she had her food those pretentiously phrased chronicles of the snobocracy […] distilling therefrom an acid '''envy''' that robbed her napoleon of all its savour.}}
#* '''1983'''.  ROSEN, Stanley.  ''Plato’s'' Sophist.  p. 66.
#*: Theodorus assures Socrates that no '''envy''' will prevent the Stranger from responding
# An object of envious notice or feeling.
#* {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay}} (1800-1859)
#*: This constitution in former days used to be the '''envy''' of the world.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} [[hatred|Hatred]], [[enmity]], ill-feeling. {{defdate|14th-18th c.}}
#* '''1485''', {{w|Thomas Malory}}, ''{{w|Le Morte d'Arthur}}'', Book X:
#*: ‘Sir,’ seyde Sir Launcelot unto Kynge Arthur, ‘by this cry that ye have made ye woll put us that bene aboute you in grete jouparté, for there be many knyghtes that hath '''envy''' to us {{...}}.’
#* '''1598''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Henry IV, Part 1}}'':
#*: But let me tell the World, / If he out-liue the '''enuie''' of this day, / England did neuer owe so sweet a hope, / So much misconstrued in his Wantonnesse.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} Emulation; rivalry.
#* {{w|John Ford (dramatist)|John Ford}} (1586-c.1639)
#*: Such as cleanliness and decency / Prompt to a virtuous '''envy'''.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} Public odium; ill repute.
#* {{w|Ben Jonson}} (1572-1637)
#*: to lay the '''envy''' of the war upon Cicero

